{"1180–December 1230":"1180–December 1230","1180–1230":"1180–1230","–Female":"Deceased","1182–1234":"1182–1234","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1210–1247":"1210–1247","1230–1284":"1230–1284","1155–1203":"1155–1203","1165–1210":"1165–1210","December 1230":"December 1230","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","15 janvier 1210":"15 January 1210","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","1203":"1203","1247":"1247","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","about 1230":"about 1230","Mirepoix, Ariege, France":"Mirepoix, Ariège, France","Lévis-Saint-Nom, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France":"Lévis-Saint-Nom, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France","Vannes, Morbihan, Brittany, France":"Vannes, Morbihan, Brittany, France","Mirepoix, Ariège, Occitanie, France":"Mirepoix, Ariège, Occitanie, France","La Roche-Bernard, Morbihan, Brittany, France":"La Roche-Bernard, Morbihan, Brittany, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"LÉvis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Levis</i> (Old English <i>Lēofhyse</i>, from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’ + <i>hyse</i> ‘youth, warrior’).","English: occasionally perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Leve</i>, Old English <i>Lēofa</i> (male) or <i>Lēofe</i> (female), which derive from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, since <i>Leve</i> is attested as a medieval surname.","English: perhaps also from Middle English <i>lef</i>, <i>leve</i>, plural <i>leves</i>, possibly representing Old English <i>lēaf</i> ‘leaf, foliage’ in some topographic sense, or Old English <i>hlīf</i> ‘shelter’."],"variants":[{"name":"Levers","meanings":["English: variant of   Lever   1 and 2, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","North German: patronymic from   Lever   3."]}]},{"name":"Guy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of a compound name starting with <i>witu</i> ‘wood’ or <i>wīt</i> ‘wide’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. In Old French initial <i>w-</i> regularly became <i>gu-</i>. The usual Norman forms of the name were <i>Gy</i> or <i>Guido</i>. In medieval Latin the same name is found as <i>Wido</i>. It was a popular name among the Normans, enhanced no doubt by the romance of Guy of Warwick, recounting the exploits of a folk hero of the Crusades."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guy De LÉvis was born in 1180, in Mirepoix, Ariège, Occitanie, France, his father, Philippe I de LEVIS, was 25 and his mother, Elisabeth de PALAISEAU, was 15. He married Guiburge De Montfort in 1210, in Mirepoix, Ariège, Occitanie, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in December 1230, in La Roche-Bernard, Morbihan, Brittany, France, at the age of 50, and was buried in Vannes, Morbihan, Brittany, France."},"et":{"1180–December 1230":"1180–detsember 1230","1180–1230":"1180–1230","–Female":"Surnud","1182–1234":"1182–1234","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1210–1247":"1210–1247","1230–1284":"1230–1284","1155–1203":"1155–1203","1165–